<DOC><DOCNO> AP890313-0161 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 2052EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-13 0471</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0481</SECOND><HEAD>More Wintry Weather Over Northern States</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snow and freezing rain were scattered across the northern Plainsand Great Lakes on Monday, and rain spread across the Southeast andthe Northwest.   A cold front extending from Canada across the northern Plainsbrought scattered snow showers to northern sections of the GreatLakes and freezing rain from western North Dakota into southernMontana.   Cold air was expected to drive southward into the northernRockies, increasing wind and bringing snow through the regionTuesday. A high wind watch was posted along the mountains ofsoutheastern Wyoming through Tuesday.   As much as 5 to 8 inches of snow was expected around theYellowstone National Park region.   A stationary front separated unseasonably warm air across theGulf Coast states from cooler air across the central Plains and OhioValley, and rain was scattered along the front from Kentucky throughNorth Carolina.   Low pressure west of Vancouver Island continued to spin off aseries of upper air disturbances across the Northwest. Showers werescattered along the northern Pacific Coast and Eugene, Ore., hadreceived 1.74 inches of rain in 24 hours.   Farther inland, 3 to 6 inches of snow fell overnight in themountains near Lake Tahoe, on the Nevada-California border, and windgusts over 70 mph were measured south of nearby Reno, Nev.   But Colorado Springs, Colo., warmed to a record 70 degrees, onedegree above the former record set in 1959.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 18degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., to 93 at Junction, Texas. Monday's lowfor the Lower 48 states was 19 degrees below zero at Fort Kent,Maine.   For Tuesday, widespread showers were forecast from the PacificNorthwest coast into northern Idaho and from northern Iowa into theupper Great Lakes and northern Illinois. Thunderstorms, somepossibly severe, were forecast from eastern Missouri and much ofKentucky across Illinois, Indiana and southern Lower Michigan intowestern Ohio. Widespread snow was forecast from the Montana Rockiesthrough the northern Plains into the upper Mississippi Valley.   Highs in the 20s were predicted from northwestern Montana throughNorth Dakota and northern Minnesota into northwestern Wisconsin; inthe 30s and 40s from the northern Rockies and the centralIntermountain areas through the middle Missouri Valley and much ofthe Great Lakes region into New England; in the 70s from thesouthern California valleys through central parts of Arizona and NewMexico, much of Oklahoma, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys into SouthCarolina; in the 80s from the desert Southwest across the southernRockies, much of Texas, the lower Mississippi Valley and Gulf Coastregion into Florida; in the 90s across the middle Rio Grande Valleyof Texas; and in the 50s or 60s across much of the rest of thenation.</TEXT></DOC>